* Nomenclature Halogenoalkanes are named in a similar manner to alkanes where the suffix ends in -ane and the halogens are treated as substituents and named as prefixes such as chloro-, homo-, iodo-. Examples: (i) CH3CH2Br (ii) CH3CH2Br (iii) CH3CH3CH3

Physical Properties

### Boiling Point

* Halogenoalkanes have a **higher boiling point** than alkanes with the same number of carbon atoms as there are **permanent dipole-permanent dipole** attractions between polar RX molecules and also **stronger instantaneous dipole-induced dipole interactions** due to the **greater number of electrons** present.
* For a given alkyl group, boiling point increases with increasing A\({}_{r}\) of the halogen. i.e. boiling point of RC/ < RBr < RI

### Solubility

* In spite of the C-X bond being polar, halogenoalkanes are **insoluble in water** due to their **inability to form hydrogen bonds with water**.
* They are **soluble** in **organic solvents** whereby the energy released from solute-solvent interactions is sufficient to overcome the solute-solute and the solvent-solvent interactions.

